<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-03-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-03-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="1049" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1049">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Sherman</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Santiago</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-03-04"><hi rend="italic">March 4,
                                1898</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 26.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The sad intelligence of the disaster to
                            the United States battle ship <hi rend="italic">Maine</hi> was received
                            here on the evening following its occurrence.</p>
                        <p>The news created widespread interest and universal sympathy. All the
                            representatives of foreign governments residing near this Government
                            called at this legation to express their sympathy. The British minister
                            was especially sympathetic and kind in his remarks, and some of the
                            British societies here have referred to the disaster in sympathetic
                            resolutions.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry L. Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>